    "summary": "The Constitutio Antoniniana (Edict of Caracalla, 212 AD) was the most sweeping legal act of the Roman imperial period — Emperor Caracalla's grant of Roman citizenship to virtually all free inhabitants of the empire, regardless of origin, transforming hundreds of millions of provincial people from subjects into citizens with full legal rights. Before 212 AD, Roman citizenship had been a privilege held by a portion of the population; after the edict, it became the default status for free people throughout the vast empire, from Britain to Mesopotamia, from the Rhineland to Egypt.\n\nThe edict's motivations were complex and somewhat cynical: a major practical effect was to subject more people to Roman inheritance taxes (from which citizens could not exempt themselves), increasing imperial revenue. The ancient historian Cassius Dio emphasized this fiscal motive. But the legal and cultural consequences extended far beyond taxation: the edict made Roman law universally applicable, accelerated the spread of Roman legal culture, facilitated administrative uniformity, and declared symbolically that the empire was a polity of citizens rather than conquered subjects. The edict is the reason why Roman law became the foundation of Western legal systems — it was the law of everyone in the empire, not merely a Roman elite. The Constitutio Antoniniana is arguably one of the most consequential legal documents in Western history, even though it was issued by an emperor (Caracalla) better known for murdering his brother Geta and massacring the population of Alexandria.",
